No one was sure. Some Norther Virginia residents who appeared showed up when it was time to talk. At least 20 showed up, though not in the hundreds that many in the audience said they wanted to see.
“I’ve seen people come, I just don’t know how many,” Crystal City businessman Mike Donnelly said in the hallway after the vote was over.
Donnelly, who is a member of the board of the Crystal City Chamber of Commerce, said he has seen a number of people from Crystal City and northern Virginia who came out for the hearing. But they did not outnumber the rest when about 500 people showed up to hear the testimony from local, state, and national government officials and stakeholders about Crystal City, competition, and incentives. It's hard to gauge the outnumbering because that was not recorded on the video.
Perhaps two thirds of all those in attendance came from the Crystal City Chamber’s business empire base in the 12761 zip code, which is the largest business center in the area, according to the chamber. <s> The write-up “Doctor had thyself” (Spectrum, October 4) took up the issue of professional ethics among doctors. Once sacrosanct Hippocratic Oath has been obscured by the British Medical Association, we have no more illusions that we will have any opportunities to protect our ultimate agency when we dictate standards to individual medical practitioners. The difficulty, of course, is not simply that the BMA has zero oversight and inappropriate pressures from government and industry; the significant nature of self-regulation (as with respect to pharmacists) is still astonishing to some observers.
Our concern here is more with the BMA’s lack of professional accountability and the fact that its actions can be interpreted by members of the public to be a form of censorship and self-censure.
In the case of the BMA, this has led to a situation in which its members can be held personally accountable for the BMA’s activities in a way in which we cannot.
In the case of the BMA itself, the situation has been exacerbated by inconsistencies in how the BMA has handled itself, and its needs to be reminded that the BMA has jurisdiction over exactly that situation.

The BMA has shown how dubious its membership is about their responsibility and accountability to the workplace and to patients as practitioners, through decisions over doses of morphine and pain medications, and in general non-enforceability of complaints ordinarily made about the practice of medicine.
In a way, BMA members can now act for themselves on the ethical issue of whether they will be held personally accountable for the decisions and actions of the BMA.

There had always been a competition between the US and Nato for Afghan skills, but the main outcomes over the past five years seem to have been occupation, political dialogue and military pacification.

Everyone bets that Afghanistan will have to split into several separate states, or at least that the "Greater" or "Pak" area will be a new state in its own right. There will probably be a new border, with the Pakistan state and Iran on one side of it. <s> I previously wrote an article stating that the Texas Primary Elections will likely be split with one in March and the other in May. This is what the Texas Republican Party and the AG argued for.
Not everyone likes that idea though, and the GOP wants to hold TXP separately, all first on the third Sunday in February, the 2022 general election on the first Saturday. The Texas GOP also wants the fall elections moved up.
The runoff elections is not really partisan, and in Jerry Madaleno's last year as AG, two Democrats ran, one was primary victorious and one was set to lose the runoff.
Madaleno did graciously step aside and let Governor Abbott pick a new AG.
There was a lot of talk about this during last year's election, and the AG said the AG could not run for re-election in 2020, and the AG would not run again in 2022 either. So it was left up for Governor Abbott to pick another AG in 2020, but she picked Jerry Madaleno instead of another person.
The GOP is still not happy with the separation though and opposed the straight two year unitary republican system. They contend that the low turnout shows that people don't like it. Crude things like "voter suppression" are starting to show up in the news media. They want these elections in conjunction.
That was a choice of an elected AG versus having an AG running for an elected office. It was that simple.
The best compromise I could find was put forth by a group of pro-AG AG candidates. It would have placed AG bets when primary elections happen. This is how all AGs do it, and that would work fine for Texas. It is not a perfect system, but it is a better system than having one office that can't run for re-election and has no real choice of an AG, which I believe would cause the AG to be more politicized.
I believe it is possible to run both elections in Texas. It will take some explaining. Most of my accomplishments as an AG and Deputy AG, effective in 2020 continuing decided the current Texas AG has been able to accomplish in office.
